The Paper Kites playing)

36:25.592 --> 36:27.225
♪

36:30.505 --> 36:32.747
Now, I know y'all
aren't trying to have

36:32.766 --> 36:34.983
a pity party without carbs.

36:36.028 --> 36:38.987
-Come on now.
-Hey, man. What's up?

36:40.032 --> 36:42.590
<i> ♪ In the morning</i>
<i> when I wake... ♪</i>

36:42.609 --> 36:44.517
What are the odds
any of this is gluten-free?

36:44.611 --> 36:47.853
No way, Cap. Those are
fully leaded, old school,

36:47.873 --> 36:49.855
everything is bad
for you donuts.

36:49.875 --> 36:52.191
Today, we eat our feelings.

36:52.211 --> 36:54.936
-Give me a bear claw.
-Oh! Well done, good choice.

36:54.955 --> 36:56.104
How about you, Marj?

36:56.197 --> 36:58.531
You know what,
just save me one with sugar.

36:58.550 --> 36:59.958
Done.

37:00.110 --> 37:02.702
<i> ♪ Shall I write it</i>
<i> in a letter? ♪</i>

37:02.721 --> 37:03.795
So glad you all came.

37:03.947 --> 37:05.964
You kidding?
We wouldn't miss it.

37:06.116 --> 37:07.782
I mean, we wouldn't
miss it again.

37:07.875 --> 37:09.726
MARJAN: Hmm.

37:09.877 --> 37:12.044
I can't lie. This one stings.

37:12.064 --> 37:15.732
Yeah. I spent the best
years of my life here.

37:15.883 --> 37:16.933
Hell, most of my life.

37:17.160 --> 37:19.552
I'm really gonna
miss this place.

37:19.571 --> 37:22.155
FOREMAN:
All right, Marty,
whenever you're ready.

37:23.725 --> 37:24.724
NANCY: Oh, man, you guys.

37:24.818 --> 37:26.968
Here we go.

37:27.061 --> 37:29.153
(cell phone chimes)

37:29.306 --> 37:32.807
<i> ♪ Can I be close to you? </i>

37:32.900 --> 37:34.167
Holy crap.

37:35.161 --> 37:36.644
I mean, holy crap.

37:36.663 --> 37:37.737
NANCY: What?

37:37.831 --> 37:39.664
Our GoFundMe to save the 126?

37:39.816 --> 37:40.924
It just got fully funded.

37:41.075 --> 37:42.667
Come on, Marj,
stop messing with us.

37:42.819 --> 37:43.835
-MARJAN: I'm not.
-Wait.

37:43.987 --> 37:45.503
Somebody gave us
$4.6 million?

37:45.655 --> 37:47.655
A whole five actually.

37:47.749 --> 37:48.840
Who would do that?

37:48.934 --> 37:50.684
Someone named Cole Robertson.

37:51.678 --> 37:52.769
-Hey! Hey!
-Hey.

37:52.920 --> 37:54.679
-Whoa, whoa, hey!
-MARJAN: Stop! Stop!

37:54.831 --> 37:56.422
OWEN: Time out. Time out.

37:56.516 --> 37:59.258
Does anyone know
who this Cole Robertson is?

37:59.278 --> 38:01.594
-No clue.
-I've never heard of him.

38:01.688 --> 38:02.687
Nope.

38:02.839 --> 38:04.672
Are we sure
he's even a real person?

38:04.766 --> 38:07.600
Oh, yeah, he's definitely real.

38:07.619 --> 38:09.619
♪

38:15.627 --> 38:18.962
I want to start by thanking
the Robertson family,

38:19.189 --> 38:21.356
whose generous gift
to the AFD

38:21.374 --> 38:23.191
allowed us all to be here
together today.

38:23.284 --> 38:24.801
It's the least we could do

38:25.028 --> 38:26.861
after what your people
did for us.

38:26.880 --> 38:28.471
(applause)

38:33.127 --> 38:35.795
OWEN:
The push-in ceremony
has its origins

38:35.814 --> 38:38.056
dating back to the 1800s

38:38.208 --> 38:42.877
when horses were used
to pull hand pumpers.

38:42.896 --> 38:44.729
But upon returning
to the station,

38:44.881 --> 38:48.716
the horses could not back up
to push in the rigs.

38:48.735 --> 38:50.234
So the firefighters

38:50.387 --> 38:53.413
had to manually push them
into the bays.

38:55.667 --> 38:56.908
In honor of that,

38:57.060 --> 38:59.577
it's become tradition
for firefighters

38:59.671 --> 39:01.563
to push their rigs in

39:01.656 --> 39:04.841
the very first time
they enter their firehouse.

39:05.068 --> 39:07.010
The push-in ceremony reminds us

39:07.161 --> 39:08.327
that even the best equipment
in the world

39:08.347 --> 39:12.140
is useless without
the people who operate it.

39:13.910 --> 39:15.927
<i> The 126 six is a family.</i>

39:16.079 --> 39:18.563
<i> These uniforms</i>
<i> bind us tighter than blood.</i>

39:19.432 --> 39:20.582
(rings bell)

39:20.600 --> 39:22.750
<i> Like a family, we argue,</i>

39:22.811 --> 39:23.860
<i> screw up...</i>

39:24.011 --> 39:24.694
(rings bell)

39:24.921 --> 39:26.029
<i> let each other down.</i>

39:26.256 --> 39:29.090
<i> But as long as we keep</i>
<i> fighting for one another,</i>

39:29.109 --> 39:32.202
<i> there is no challenge</i>
<i> that we cannot rise to.</i>

39:32.429 --> 39:35.872
<i> There is no crisis</i>
<i> that we cannot overcome.</i>

39:36.023 --> 39:38.208
<i> This building</i>
<i> stands today</i>

39:38.435 --> 39:40.526
<i> not because</i>
<i> of its bricks and mortar,</i>

39:40.545 --> 39:42.954
<i> but because of the heart</i>
<i> and the soul of the family</i>

39:43.106 --> 39:44.547
<i> inside of it.</i>

39:44.774 --> 39:46.341
126.

39:47.127 --> 39:49.177
And so it shall always be.

39:52.799 --> 39:54.307
(rings bell)

39:55.877 --> 39:57.560
(applause)

39:58.897 --> 40:01.189
(indistinct chatter)

40:02.292 --> 40:03.382
(both yell)

40:03.627 --> 40:05.384
That's what I'm talkin' about.
That's game, baby!

40:05.404 --> 40:07.070
PAUL: No way!
My girl Lindsey's puck

40:07.221 --> 40:09.297
wins it for team red
in a squeaker.

40:09.315 --> 40:10.815
MATEO:
I think you've had
too much punch, Paul.

40:10.909 --> 40:12.091
Nancy's is definitely
the winning puck.

40:12.093 --> 40:13.410
PAUL: Oh... Hey, Marjan. Marjan.

40:13.637 --> 40:14.577
Which puck is further?

40:14.729 --> 40:16.228
I'm gonna have to go
with whichever one

40:16.322 --> 40:17.747
belongs to the daughter
of the man

40:17.899 --> 40:20.417
